align=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Proper ways to address people?</span><hr size=1> Always being curious in how this works, what would be the proper &quot;addressing&quot; to people in Japanese? I'm sure everyone is familar with the &quot;-chan&quot;, &quot;-san&quot;, etc. titles, but I'd like to know what would be considered &quot;modern&quot; in these days, instead of having to rely on the Western interpretations/stereotypes (e.g. &quot;Kun is only for guys, chan for girls&quot;, etc.).<br>
<br>
I pretty much ask this since it's been bugging me for some time; &quot;-kun&quot; was typically thought to refer to just fellows that are friends or co-workers/students of a lower grade. Nowadays, I've caught wind of girls being referred with &quot;-kun&quot;, often by friends of theirs. So I guess I'm asking for all the appropriate times a person can be referred to as &quot;-san&quot;, &quot;-chan&quot;, etc.<br>
<br>
Also, there's that &quot;you&quot; reference; my Japanese friend once mentioned that a girl shouldn't refer to a male classmate (or similar) as &quot;anata&quot;, but moreso &quot;anta&quot;, as the former was like referring to him as a boyfriend or husband. ^^; I've neglected to ask her for a clear explanation, so I'm asking those of here who have more of an idea than I do.<br>
<br>
If anyone can clear those two up (they're mainly for my future reference), I'd be very grateful. Thank you in advance. <p><center><hr width="50%"><br><br><IMG SRC="http://webpost.net/wi/withroo/harusig1.jpg" USEMAP="#harusig1.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=110 BORDER=0>
