usually between friends you can drop the titles completely, and just use the names. <br>
kun, chan etc etc. &quot;stereotypes&quot; are still correct (kun for guys, chan for girls, try to avoid calling everyone &quot;chan&quot; if you're a guy unless you want to squarely fix yourself as an otaku, etc.)  However, just like in english, these rules are often broken.<br>
<br>
many girls (especially in big cities) will use stereotypically &quot;male&quot; words to refer to each other to add a touch of &quot;roughness&quot; or &quot;coolness&quot; etc. to their way of speech. So yes, girls can call each other ~kun, &quot;anta&quot; and even &quot;omae&quot; (among others)- but this way of talking is reserved more for the shibuya/harajuku populace.  I doubt you'd find this as widespread in Shimane, for example.  Some girls (the thugged out kind that put even the ganguro to shame) even use &quot;ore&quot; to refer to themselves.  While I can't fully appreciate the subtleties that the usage of such relatively &quot;rude&quot; male terms by girls has, I do know that it's not &quot;pretty&quot; in sense.  But just as in the west, this all has to do with the girl and her particular character/image she wants to convey (just like you have rough-neck girls who swear worse than sailors or want-to-apply-to-a-convent girls who still exclaim &quot;sugar&quot; when they stub their toes (and then apologise!))<br>
<br>
The reason why i spent so much time on the girls is that for guys (as far as i know) it's still &quot;ore&quot;, &quot;omae&quot; and no title suffix when speaking to one another.  So that stereotype is pretty accurate, I guess.<br>
<br>
As far as &quot;anata/anta&quot;.  Since I'm not a japanese schoolgirl, I asked my friend who is about this.  Her response was that &quot;anata&quot; sounds distant and is rarely used (for that reason) in referring to both males and females and doesn't necessarily convey a sense of a relationship (which i tend to concur with based on my own experience).  Usually between friends they tend just to use the name (with no suffix, again).<br>
<br>
&quot;Anta&quot; is rude in just about every sense of the word.  Used when angry (like when chewing someone out) and in similar situations.  Of course, as mentioned before, some girls like to use such &quot;rougher&quot; words in everyday conversation as a style thing.<br>
<br>
I should add, however, that my friend's from a small town.  I have no idea what the latest tokyo etc. slang is. <p><center><B> <I>Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu.  <BR>Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.  </I> </B></center>
